{{Quote|Star Wars design is more sophisticated than it first appears. On the surface, the designs may seem simple and obvious, and that's intentional. But underneath lie layers of foundational guidelines that shape this cohesive universe. In reality, only George truly knows what Star Wars design is. I do my best, but I don't always get it 100 per cent right.|Doug Chiang|<ref name="Bloq">{{WebCite|url=https://www.creativebloq.com/art/digital-art/doug-chiang-reveals-what-it-takes-to-make-it-as-a-star-wars-artist-focus-on-being-better-than-who-you-were-yesterday|text=Doug Chiang reveals what it takes to make it as a Star Wars artist: "Focus on being better than who you were yesterday"|work=[https://www.creativebloq.com/ Creative Bloq]|archivedate=20251129184053}}</ref>}}
'''Doug Chiang''' is an American illustrator and art director who has worked on several major ''[[Star Wars]]'' projects. Born in [[Wikipedia:Taiwan|Taiwan]] and raised in [[Wikipedia:Michigan|Michigan]], Doug Chiang joined [[Industrial Light & Magic]] and was later selected by [[George Lucas]] to head the art departments of [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''The Phantom Menace'']] and [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Attack of the Clones'']]. As of [[2021]], he has since become vice president and executive creative director at [[Lucasfilm]], responsible for overseeing designs for all new ''Star Wars'' franchise developments, such as the [[sequel trilogy]] and [[Star Wars Anthology Series|anthology]] films, theme parks, [[Star Wars video games|games]], and the ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan Kenobi]]'' television series.

==Biography==
[[File:PodraceCrashDougChiang.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Doug Chiang's concept drawing "[[Podracing|Podrace]] Crash"]]
Doug Chiang lived in [[Wikipedia:Taiwan|Taiwan]] until he moved with his family to [[Wikipedia:Michigan|Michigan]] in the United States at around five years old. Chiang parents spoke a [[Wikipedia:Languages of Taiwan|Taiwanese language]] with some [[Wikipedia:Taiwanese Mandarin|Mandarin]], but he and his siblings were encouraged to assimilate, learning English and eventually losing their [[Wikipedia:Chinese language|Chinese language]] skills. Chiang described his family as very [[Wikipedia:Chinese culture|culturally Chinese]] despite trying to fit in American society.<ref name="APAHM" /> Chiang grew up in Detroit.<ref name="secrets" />

Chiang had started drawing when four years old, and he could remember his disappointment with some toys, his inclination to imagine better ones, and create his own things. By high school he made drawings of futuristic vehicles.<ref name="secrets" />

Although art was discouraged as a career prospect, Chiang developed an interest in film after watching [[1977]]'s [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']] and [[Wikipedia:Ray Harryhausen|Ray Harryhausen's]] [[Wikipedia:The Golden Voyage of Sinbad|''The Golden Voyage of Sinbad'']]. He was particularly inspired by the insight into film production in the documentary ''[[The Making of Star Wars]]''. Chiang later went to study at [[Wikipedia:University of California|UCLA]].<ref name="APAHM" /><ref name="secrets" /> He spent summer nights in the basement of his house making cardboard models of creatures and vehicles, and filming them using stop-motion animation in 8 mm.<ref name="secrets" />

In [[1989]], Chiang joined [[Industrial Light & Magic]]. As a professional, he used to take photographs of unusual objects he came across, and catalogue them for future reference, such as machines that would become an inspiration for a spaceship design.<ref name="secrets" />

After ''[[Wikipedia:Jumanji|Jumanji]]'', he left ILM in [[1995]] to serve as the Design Director for [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''The Phantom Menace'']] and he moved from San Rafael to [[Skywalker Ranch]] to consult with [[George Lucas]] about his illustrations. Around this time, he joined the ''[[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire]]'' multimedia project and the design of the new spaceships.<ref name="secrets" />

Chiang returned as Concept Design Supervisor for [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Attack of the Clones'']] and as a concept artist for [[Star Wars: Episode VII The Force Awakens|''Star Wars'': Episode VII ''The Force Awakens'']].<ref name="Insider 145">{{InsiderCite|145|Shaping the Past}}</ref> He is currently one of the members of the [[Intellectual Property Development Group]].<ref name="Art Last Jedi">''[[The Art of Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]''</ref>

Chiang served as a production designer and co-producer for the ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan Kenobi]]'' television series.<ref name="Part V">{{Kenobi|Part V}}</ref> He created many of the original concepts for the [[Reva's lightsaber|Third Sister's lightsaber]]. When the prop makers were building the unique design, they took into account Chiang's artistic vision as well as director [[Deborah Chow]]'s need in bringing the action sequences with the [[Reva Sevander|Third Sister]] to life.<ref name="Weapons of Inquis">{{SW|url=news/inside-the-lucasfilm-archive-obi-wan-kenobi-props-2|text=Inside the Lucasfilm Archive: Weapons of the Inquisitorius from the ''Obi-Wan Kenobi'' Limited Series}}</ref> Chiang gave input into the overall look of [[Hayden Christensen]] playing [[Anakin Skywalker|Darth Vader]] in a [[bacta tank]].<ref name="Christensen Hollywood">{{WebCite|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-features/obi-wan-kenobi-hayden-christensen-darth-vader-anakin-sand-feelings-1235162358|text='Obi-Wan Kenobi' Star Hayden Christensen Explores His Latest Darth Vader Incarnation and Talks Anakin's (Much-Memed) Sand Feelings|author=Ryan Parker|date=2022-06-13|work=[[Wikipedia:The Hollywood Reporter|''The Hollywood Reporter'']]|archivedate=20220613130155}}</ref>

[[File:KP-1DrawingDougChiang.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Drawings of KP-1 done by Doug Chiang and the art department over Camille Manet's drawing]]
The [[Wikipedia:French people|French]] fan [[Camille Manet]] was named the grand prize winner of the Build My Droid contest for her design of the [[droid]] [[KP-1]].<ref name="Build My Droid article">{{SW|url=news/kp-1-obi-wan-kenobi|text=How a ''Star Wars'' Fan Created a New Droid for Disney+'s ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''}}</ref> Chiang loved Manet's concept of KP-1. In [[March]], [[2021]], Chiang, Chow, and other crew members met virtually to discuss what purpose KP-1 could serve in the show. Chow suggested that the droid could be put in the "pseudo rebel base" and have some functionality. Chiang wanted to preserve all of the key elements in the concept and also bring practicality so that it could interact with the actors. Chiang and the art department did a drawing of KP-1 over Manet's drawing. The droid's head, [[Photoreceptor|eye]], and markings were modeled after an [[R2-series astromech droid]].<ref name="BMD Contest">{{SWYouTube|QrSKKyWhZvU|Build My Droid Contest &#124; Obi-Wan Kenobi &#124; Disney+}}</ref> Manet met virtually with Chiang who put some finishing touches on KP-1 for filming.<ref name="Build My Droid article" />

